Funding: National Science Foundation Division of Behavioral and Cognitive Sciences (BCS-1835317)
EthicsApprovals: University of Florida Institutional Review Board (IRB201801727)

Question1.Description: Experience/Skill Survey, for TABLE TENNIS specifically: How often do you play table tennis?

Question2.Description: Experience/Skill Survey, for TABLE TENNIS specifically: In your life, how many organized (sanctioned) table tennis events have you competed in (i.e., tournaments or league matches)?

Question3.Description: Experience/Skill Survey, for TABLE TENNIS specifically: Describe your highest level of experience in table tennis.

Question4.Description: Experience/Skill Survey, for TABLE TENNIS specifically: In your life, how many unorganized table tennis games have you competed in (i.e., garage-style or bar matches with friends)?

Question5.Description: Experience/Skill Survey, for RACQUET SPORTS other than table tennis: How often do you play other racquet sports?

Question6.Description: Experience/Skill Survey, for RACQUET SPORTS other than table tennis: In your life, how many other organized (sanctioned) racquet sport events have you competed in (i.e., tournaments or league matches)?

Question7.Description: Experience/Skill Survey, for RACQUET SPORTS other than table tennis: Describe your highest level of experience in other racquet sports.

Question8.Description: Experience/Skill Survey, for RACQUET SPORTS other than table tennis: In your life, how many unorganized racquet sport games have you competed in (i.e., friendly weekend matches)?

Question9.Description: Experience/Skill Survey, for all racquet sports (INCLUDING table tennis): What is your primary racquet sport (Please pick one).

1.0.2 2023-06-06
  - Added "Merged" files to the sourcedata folder. These are filtered at 1 Hz high-pass and the individual LiveAmps are merged along with the Cometas IMUs
1.0.1 2023-03-30
  - add files and source data
README:
Our dataset contains high-density, dual-layer electroencephalography (EEG), neck electromyography (EMG), inertial measurement unit (IMU) acceleration, T1 structural MR images, and video data from 25 participants playing real-world table tennis. Participants played 60 minutes of table tennis (in total) with a ball machine and a human player, with an additional 10 minutes of standing baseline. For 17 of the participants, we also include video data of all trials. The Adobe Premiere project files (linked to each video) have the timing of hit events marked.

Data in the main subject folders have been processed. We include the ICA decomposition and dipole model in EEG.etc. The components retained in our analyses are shown in EEG.etc.KeepComponents. The raw data can be found in the sourcedata folder.    

Please refer to our publication for more details.

sub-01_task-TableTennis_eeg.json.InstitutionalDepartmentName: J. Crayton Pruitt Family Department of Biomedical Engineering
sub-01_task-TableTennis_eeg.json.Instructions: Avoid clenching your jaw, stay as relaxed as possible during the trials. For cooperative trials with a human player, work together to keep as many balls in play as possible. For competitive games, try winning a 21-point game against the human player, switching serves every five points. For stationary ball machine trials, the ball will come to the center of the table, stay in the same place to hit the balls. For moving ball machine trials, the balls will come toward all parts of the table, feel free to move as you normally would to hit the ball. We did not instruct participants to hit a specific target on the table nor to hit specific types of shots.
sub-01_task-TableTennis_eeg.json.TaskDescription: Participants played table tennis with a human and a ball machine in four 15-minute blocks of trials. In a single block, participants played 7.5 minutes with a human player for half of the trials (cooperative or competitive play) and the other 7.5 minutes were played against a ball machine (3 back-to-back 2.5 minute trials that alternated between stationary and moving conditions). Half of the ball machine trials fed the ball to the participant on one bounce (replicating a rally shot), and the other half fed the ball on two bounces (replicating a serve). The order of trials among and within blocks was randomized.

trial_type.Description: Primary categorization of each trial to identify them as instances of the experimental conditions (equivalent to the EEG.event.condlabel field in the data).

Levels.competitive: Competitive games with a human player
Levels.cooperative: Cooperative hitting with a human player
Levels.moving_hit: Ball machine; machine was oscillating; 1 bounce
Levels.moving_serve: Ball machine; machine was oscillating; 2 bounces
Levels.stationary_hit: Ball machine; machine was not oscillating; 1 bounce
Levels.stationary_serve: Ball machine; machine was not oscillating; 2 bounces

value.Description: Type of event (equivalent to the EEG.event.type field in the data).

Levels.M 1: Sync event recorded with BrainVision system
Levels.Subject_hit: The participant's paddle made contact with the ball
Levels.Subject_receive: The ball machine fed OR the human opponent's paddle made contact with the ball
